ion ignored warnings inept disaster response and commonplace human error furthermore despite the best attempts to forestall them normal accidents will inevitably occur in the complex tightly coupled systems of modern society resulting in the kind of unpredictable cascading disaster seen at the fukushima daiichi nuclear power station government and business can always do more to prevent serious accidents through regulation design training and mindfulness even so some complex systems with catastrophic potential are just too dangerous to exist because they cannot be made safe regardless of human effort downloads pdf+ fukushima and the inevitability of accidents by charles perrow modified december 2011 pdf fukushima_and_the_inevitabilit pdf 111.0 kb html+ go to site external http bos sagepub com content 67 6 parent research nuclear security and risk topics business disaster response history nuclear power search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publication news charles perrow discusses the inevitability of accidents cisac fsi stanford publications of interest fukushima what don t we know rodney c ewing jeroen ritsema bulletin of the atomic scientists 2011 html+ pdf+ nuclear power post fukushima presentation robert rosner steve goldberg 2011 pdf+ cover coordinations under large uncertainty an analysis of the fukushima catastrophe masahiko aoki geoffrey rothwell social science research network 2011 html+ cover learning from normal accidents scott d sagan organization and environment vol 17 1 2004 pdf+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4581 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
